{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17471750","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17471750"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T21:51:10+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T21:51:10+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"656"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"656","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/656"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.01,0.03,0.02,0.89]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"656"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"41580"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"656","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/656"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"656"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"26500"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"13"},{"type":"tags","id":"35"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1046"},{"type":"tags","id":"1396"},{"type":"tags","id":"4954"},{"type":"tags","id":"4959"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"7891"},{"type":"tags","id":"11638"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"5021"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6202"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44031"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44924"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"41580","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/41580"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 17-year-old student presents with recurrent left-sided epistaxis, occurring about once every 1 - 2 weeks over the last three months. His last episode was five days ago, lasted almost an hour and he mainly noticed blood running down the back of his throat.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe patient reports long-standing left nasal obstruction. There is no history of nasal trauma or head injury. He reports no easy bruising, weight loss, or other B-symptoms. He plays high grade competitive sport and is doing well in school, stating that he has not felt more tired recently.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAnterior nasal examination shows a dark purple mass from the posterior nose filling the nasal cavity. The patient\u0027s orbital exam is normal and he is haemodynamically stable.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Von Willebrand disease","Leukaemia","Nasopharyngeal carcinoma","Foreign body","Juvenile nasopharyngeal angiofibroma"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EJuvenile nasopharyngeal angiofibroma\u003C/strong\u003E is a benign growth occurring in adolescent males. These growths bleed extensively, other symptoms include nasal obstruction, rhinorrhoea, anosmia and headaches.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVon Willebrand disease\u003C/strong\u003E is less likely due to the lack of evidence of other heavy bleeding such as menorrhagia or easy bruising.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELeukaemia\u003C/strong\u003E must always be considered for patients presenting with recurrent epistaxis, however the lack of systemic symptoms such as fatigue and weight loss make this less likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EForeign Bodies\u003C/strong\u003E are a common cause of nasal obstruction and potential epistaxis in young children, it would be uncommon for an adolescent to present with an intranasal foreign body with no recollection of how it got there.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENasopharyngeal carcinoma \u003C/strong\u003Ehas a peak incidence in the 4th and 6th decades of life and most commonly occurs in South-East asian populations and long term smokers. The red flags suggestive of nasopharyngeal carcinoma are: facial pain/ headaches, unilateral nasal blockage, otalgia, loose teeth, facial swelling, or may present with cervical lymphadenopathy.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Consider juvenile nasopharyngeal angiofibroma in adolescent male patients with recurring epistaxis"],"references":["Yau S. An update on epistaxis. Australian Family Physician. 2015;44(9):653-656.","Dai Y. Nasopharyngeal Cancer - Oncology - Medbullets Step 2/3 [Internet]. Step2.medbullets.com. 2022 [cited 15 May 2022]. Available from: https://step2.medbullets.com/oncology/121744/nasopharyngeal-cancer"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"26500"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"656"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"26500","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/26500"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-01-18T17:27:57+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-01-18T17:27:57+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"656"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"41580"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"13","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/13"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\ude78","name":"Haematology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:44+10:30"},"relationship